#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/for-maintainability/naming.md:1
msgid "Naming"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/for-maintainability/naming.md:3
msgid "Be descriptive (`descriptive-names`)"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/for-maintainability/naming.md:5
msgid ""
"Choose names that convey meaning at the point of use. Avoid single-letter "
"names and ambiguous abbreviations. Prefer full words over cryptic shorthand "
"so that readers do not need surrounding context to understand a variable's "
"purpose. Prefer names that are as short as possible while still being "
"unambiguous at the point of use."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/for-maintainability/naming.md:13
msgid "Be accurate (`accurate-names`)"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/for-maintainability/naming.md:15
msgid ""
"Avoid confusing names. If a name can be misread to imply the wrong meaning, "
"behavior, or side effects, it must be corrected immediately."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/for-maintainability/naming.md:21
msgid "// Good — clearly a count\n"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/for-maintainability/naming.md:22
msgid ""
"// Bad — looks like a collection\n"
"// rather than a numeric counter\n"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/for-maintainability/naming.md:28
msgid "Choose verbs that reflect the actual work being done."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/for-maintainability/naming.md:32
msgid "// Good — implies an MMIO read is involved\n"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/for-maintainability/naming.md:33
#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/for-maintainability/naming.md:35
#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/for-maintainability/naming.md:42
#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/for-maintainability/naming.md:44
msgid "/* .. */"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/for-maintainability/naming.md:34
msgid "// Bad — looks like a plain field access\n"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/for-maintainability/naming.md:41
msgid "// Good — implies an O(n) collection pass\n"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/for-maintainability/naming.md:43
msgid "// Bad — sounds like an accessor returning a reference\n"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/for-maintainability/naming.md:48
msgid ""
"See also: PR [\\#1488](https://github.com/asterinas/asterinas/"
"pull/1488#discussion_r1825441287) and [\\#2964](https://github.com/asterinas/"
"asterinas/pull/2964#discussion_r2789739882)."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/for-maintainability/naming.md:52
msgid "Encode units and important attributes in names (`encode-units`)"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/for-maintainability/naming.md:54
msgid ""
"When the type does not encode the unit, the name must. Kernel code deals "
"with bytes, pages, frames, nanoseconds, ticks, and sectors — ambiguous units "
"are a source of real bugs."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/for-maintainability/naming.md:60
msgid ""
"```text\n"
"// Good — unit is unambiguous\n"
"timeout_ns\n"
"offset_bytes\n"
"size_pages\n"
"delay_ms\n"
"\n"
"// Bad — unit is ambiguous\n"
"timeout\n"
"offset\n"
"size\n"
"delay\n"
"```"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/for-maintainability/naming.md:74
msgid ""
"Where the language's type system can enforce units (e.g., newtypes), prefer "
"that. Where it cannot, the name must carry the information."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/for-maintainability/naming.md:78
msgid ""
"See also: PR [\\#2796](https://github.com/asterinas/asterinas/"
"pull/2796#discussion_r2646889913)."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/for-maintainability/naming.md:81
msgid "Use assertion-style boolean names (`bool-names`)"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/for-maintainability/naming.md:83
msgid ""
"Boolean variables and functions should read as assertions of fact. Use "
"`is_`, `has_`, `can_`, `should_`, `was_`, or `needs_` prefixes. Never use "
"negated names (`is_not_empty`, `no_error`); prefer the positive form "
"(`is_empty`, `ok` or `succeeded`). A bare name like `found`, `done`, or "
"`ready` is acceptable when the context is unambiguous."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/for-maintainability/naming.md:95
msgid "// Good — reads as an assertion\n"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/for-maintainability/naming.md:99
msgid "// Bad — verb suggests an action, not a query\n"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/for-maintainability/naming.md:101
msgid "// Bad — negated name\n"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/for-maintainability/naming.md:106
msgid ""
"See also: PR [\\#1488](https://github.com/asterinas/asterinas/"
"pull/1488#discussion_r1841827039)."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/for-maintainability/naming.md:109
msgid "Format error messages consistently (`error-message-format`)"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/for-maintainability/naming.md:111
msgid ""
"Start with a lowercase letter (unless the first word is a proper noun or "
"identifier). Be specific: prefer \"`len` is too large\" over \"the argument "
"is invalid\"."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/for-maintainability/naming.md:116
msgid ""
"For system call errors, follow the style and descriptions in Linux man pages."
msgstr ""
